<TEXT>
rio de janeiro wants 54 million 
from the federal government to avoid bankruptcy but federal 
officials said tuesday that bailing out this celebrated tourist 
mecca would set a bad precedent 
presidential press spokesman carlos henrique santos told 
reporters that if president jose sarney helps rio the next day 
there will be a line of 4000 mayors knocking on the door of the 
presidential palace 
rio mayor roberto saturnino braga said last week that his city 
of 5 million people was broke and could not pay its debts or the 
salaries of 100000 municipal employees unless rio received federal 
aid 
rio is brazils secondlargest city and a major tourist 
attraction but finance minister mailson da nobrega has refused the 
citys request to issue 54 million in emergency bonds 
rio has been hurt in the last few decades by the transfer of the 
federal capital to brasilia and the flight of industry to sao 
paulo the nations largest city 
today rio owes about 150 million to brazilian creditors and 
another 150 million in foreign debts the city has projected a 
budget deficit of close to 180 million this year 
saturnino braga warned that the city may have to cut off school 
lunches and medical supplies to city hospitals unless its credit is 
extended 
the mayor a former economist who belongs to the fledgling 
brazilian socialist party also said the city was considering 
selling the nelson piquet autodrome named for its famous race car 
driver and the site of the annual brazilian formula 1 grand prix 
he predicted financial chaos unless the city received aid 
there could be a deterioration of the city chaos general 
strikes deterioration of public services and the conservation of 
the city but well do everything possible to avoid bankruptcy he 
said in an interview over the weekend with the jornal do brasil 
newspaper of rio 
</TEXT>
