<TEXT>
representatives of the nicaraguan 
government and rebel leaders met for the first time in three months 
monday but broke off talks after failing to agree on a new location 
for resuming peace negotiations 
the rebel delegation rejected the governments demand that 
future talks to end the 7yearold civil war take place in the 
nicaraguan capital of managua rebel leader roberto ferrey said 
after the meeting 
the rebels proposed guatemala costa rica or the dominican 
republic as alternative sites for highlevel negotiations ferrey 
said 
mondays meeting had been called as a preliminary step to 
resuming the peace talks that collapsed june 9 the fourhour 
session was the first meeting between the leftist government and 
the usbacked rebels since talks collapsed 
a possible second day of talks on tuesday was ruled out and no 
date for another meeting was announced 
ferrey said rebels were open to considering new proposals on a 
location for the talks and the government has said it would keep 
trying to persuade the rebels to bargain in managua 
ferrey said he reiterated a rebel proposal that highlevel talks 
be held sept 2628 but not in managua the proposal was contained 
in a letter he submitted to nicaraguan deputy foreign minister 
victor hugo tinoco head of the government delegation and was made 
available to reporters 
the rebels known as contras also demanded the government 
release more than 40 opposition demonstrators arrested in july and 
guarantee freedom of expression as a precondition to further talks 
ferrey said that during previous talks in managua rebel leaders 
felt like prisoners in their own country and added our 
telephone conversations were listened to he did not elaborate 
in a separate press conference tinoco said the government was 
sticking by its position that the talks be held in managua 
a fragile march 21 ceasefire remains in effect in nicaragua 
but each side accuses the other of violating the truce 
tinoco had said before the meeting monday he expected it to 
result in a ceasefire for 30 or 60 days that could be extended 
indefinitely there was no announcement on extending the 
ceasefire 
both sides had agreed on march 23 to seek a negotiated 
settlement to the conflict the government says has claimed the 
lives of 28000 nicaraguans 
tinoco said monday that that agreement called for managua as the 
site of peace negotiations 
the agreement called on the rebels to lay down their arms in 
exchange for democratic reforms shortly before peace talks broke 
off in june the sandinistas proposed a timetable for disarmament 
and political reforms 
but the contras rejected the plan saying it did not go far 
enough they demanded freedom for political prisoners and 
democratic reforms in nicaragua before disarming 
tinoco said the sandinistas will urge that a ceasefire 
verification commission funded by 10 million from congress be put 
into operation commission members would include the 
secretarygeneral of the organization of american states joao 
baena soares and nicaraguan cardinal miguel obando y bravo 
tinoco also reiterated the governments demand that the contras 
free 66 prisoners of war being held in honduras 
he blamed the contras for ending peace talks on june 9 the 
contras broke them off to seek military aid in the united states 
congress he said 
direct us military aid to the rebels ended feb 29 and the 
contras have few bargaining chips left nonlethal us aid to the 
contras is distributed only in honduras 
during the past four months most of the rebel forces fled back 
to base camps inside honduras to receive new supplies of uniforms 
and food 
contra sources say only 2000 fighters remain inside nicaragua 
while more than 9000 are holed up in isolated camps in eastern 
honduras 
the ceasefire pact in march caused deep divisions within the 
rebel ranks militant contras led by enrique bermudez a former 
colonel under the deposed anastasio somoza dictatorship said the 
agreement was tantamount to surrender 
</TEXT>
