<TEXT>
the race for us senate between gop 
incumbent david karnes and democratic challenger bob kerrey has 
been disrupted by a thirdparty candidate a maverick legislator 
who was nominated at a convention held in a fastfood restaurant 
kerrey a former oneterm governor who is leading in the polls 
boycotted sunday what was to have been the second of eight campaign 
debates after organizers agreed to include state sen ernie 
chambers candidate of the leftwing new alliance party 
kerrey said monday he would engage in future debates with karnes 
only if the incumbent barred chambers and renounced the new 
alliance party which kerrey characterized as a fringe group bent 
on disrupting the political process 
the issue is whether the new alliance party deserves to be in 
our debates kerrey said i have said no i have said that a 
party of 14 members that holds its nominating convention in booth 
no 2 at dennys restaurant should not be included 
karnes called chambers a legitimate candidate who had a right to 
participate in the debates but on monday karnes said he would 
not be debating any further and blamed kerrey for the breakdown 
bob kerrey is the debatebuster in this campaign he said 
i believe kerrey has accomplished his goal of destroying the 
debate process i do not believe it will do me any good to 
continue 
the first debate certainly did karnes little good speaking at 
the state fair in lincoln on sept 5 he was booed when he said 
we need fewer farmers karnes who in one of his commercials 
picks up a bale of hay and is described as the farmersenator said 
the remark was a slip of the tongue 
karnes a lawyer for an omaha grain company was plucked from 
political obscurity in 1986 when newly elected gop gov kay orr 
chose him to succeed democratic sen edward zorinsky who died of a 
heart attack 
analysts believe karnes stands to gain from chambers candidacy 
chambers who is black is very popular in the predominantly 
lowincome democraticvoting north omaha district he has 
represented in the legislature for 18 years blacks make up about 
12 percent of omahas population and there are few blacks in the 
state outside its largest city 
chambers a barber has a long history of controversy in 
nebraska politics while most state senators wear suits on the 
floor of the legislature chambers wears a sweat shirt and blue 
jeans he once called libyan leader moammar gadhafi a great man 
and said president reagan was a ramboesque character in the last 
stages of senility 
chambers acknowledged that his candidacy could hurt kerrey but 
added it would be a mistake it would diminish me as a person 
and the significance of what im about to say im running this 
race to stop bob kerrey chambers said 
i want to stop both of them i want to win 
but stopping the democrats nationally is an avowed goal of the 
new alliance party a blackled organization that describes itself 
as multiracial leftist opposed to contra aid and nuclear weapons 
and favoring more rights for women and homosexuals 
in omaha last week new alliance presidential candidate lenora 
fulani said her campaign sought to dump dukakis 
it would give me great joy to spoil for a party that has come 
into the afroamerican community and other communities in this 
county and taken our vote taken our hope taken our desire and 
turned it into a dukakislloyd bentsen ticket ms fulani said 
an omaha worldherald poll released sunday showed kerrey favored 
by 51 percent of the 755 registered voters questioned by telephone 
statewide sept 1416 karnes was favored by 33 percent and 
chambers had 4 percent eleven percent said they were undecided 
the poll had a margin of error of 36 percent 
ironically kerrey was the original new alliance senate nominee 
in the may 10 primary the former governor received 20 new alliance 
writein votes and chambers finished fourth with five votes kerrey 
declined the nomination and chambers was chosen in july at a state 
convention held at a dennys restaurant 
chambers who also was running unopposed for reelection to his 
seat in the legislature accepted the nomination after the courts 
ruled he could not run for two offices simultaneously chambers 
elected to remain on the senate ballot and said he would mount a 
writein legislative campaign 
