<TEXT>
pope john paul iis 10day swing through 
africa has paradoxically served to reduce the stigma of any future 
visit to south africa while firmly including the vatican as a 
player in efforts to solve the regions conflicts 
an unexpected touchdown in johannesburg involvement in a 
hostage drama in lesotho and quiet diplomacy to nudge mozambique 
and south africa away from confrontation marked a trip which 
initially had only the trappings of the fourth papal pastoral visit 
to the continent 
you could say it was an act of grace commented vatican 
secretary of state agostino casaroli pondering the consequences 
after bad weather forced a landing in south africa the very 
country whose racial policies the pope excoriated at his first 
touchdown in zimbabwe 
before john pauls visit to zimbabwe botswana lesotho 
swaziland and mozambique some bishops and african leaders urged 
him to strike the nation of apartheid from any future travel but 
by the time the pope landed in rome monday night few voices 
against a future stopover had been raised 
even the rev allan boesak the protestant antiapartheid leader 
who attended a papal ecumenical papal meeting in maputo 
mozambique stopped short of discouraging a trip despite his 
charges that the pope had been too soft on the white minority 
government 
vatican prelates confirmed the pope would fly to madagascar and 
tanzania in 1989 and that he was considering a visit to rigidly 
marxist angola 
a customary vatican procedure is to include countries of the 
same region on one trip making the prospect of a south africa trip 
in the near future a distinct possibility 
after all the pope had now landed at jan smuts airport sipped 
tea with foreign minister pik botha ridden 190 miles in a 
bulletproof government sedan stopped for refreshments at an 
afrikaner gas station and visited people injured in the storming in 
lesotho of a hijacked bus during which six people were killed by 
south african commandos 
the pope who has rarely held back from sensitive subjects on 
his foreign tours continued to speak out 
he lectured the 20yearold king of swaziland and his four 
wives about polygamy 
he repeatedly nudged mozambiques marxist government 
overwhelmed by 6 million people on the edge of famine and by the 
ravages of a civil war to sit down at the negotiating table with 
rebels offering the churchs help if needed 
the latter subject was all the more delicate since president 
joaquim chissanos government until recently held on to confiscated 
church property while the mozambique resistance movement a 
shadowy group holding much of the country tried to depict itself 
to the vatican and the outside world as anticommunist and thus in 
favor of religious freedom 
john paul set his own agenda in some of the most graphic 
speeches of any papal trip exclaming yes my beloved brothers 
i have felt the heart of this country bleed i am taking home 
images of suffering the worried gaze of many children the look 
of uncertainty of so many youths the tired eyes of so many adults 
and the sad look of the aged 
becoming unusually specific he has permitted mozambican bishops 
to encourage negotiations between the government and rebels while 
backing a government program of amnesty which has already convinced 
2000 rebels to lay down their weapons 
the popes trip was like rain on scorched earth commented 
nampula bishop dom manuel vieira pinto saying it marked a turning 
point in churchstate relations 
on the government side jose luis cabaco head of the ruling 
frelimo partys foreign relations department said mozambique could 
endorse practically everything the pope had recommended 
cabaco added that the government also felt encouraged by the 
vatican in mozambiques efforts to revive a nonaggression pact and 
economic cooperation with south africa and by the popes worldwide 
appeal for aid 
according to diplomats who spoke on condition of anonymity the 
vatican as it has done in the case of poland and other countries 
is dangling the prospect of formal diplomatic relations with 
mozambique as an incentive for it to continue supporting the 
regional peace process and the thaw in religious freedom 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
rome bureau chief dennis redmont has covered the 
papacy since 1975 
