<TEXT>
a national dairy promotion program financed by 
dairy farmers should be tightened to eliminate slipshod accounting 
methods waste and unauthorized use of funds an agriculture 
department audit says 
the report by the usdas office of inspector general criticized 
the agricultural marketing service which administers the program 
for not providing adequate guidelines and controls over those 
sharing in the funds and for submitting incomplete information to 
congress 
ams annual report to congress did not include information 
relating to approximately 60 percent of the activities of the 
program the auditors said congress had not been informed as 
to the accountability of approximately 3744 million of 6197 
million of the dairy promotion program assessments for the 
threeyear period ending april 30 1987 
the inspector generals office said it was looking into at least 
one case of possible fraud however it declined to provide details 
and said only that a report on the investigation would be issued 
later 
the program was created by congress in a 1983 law that imposes a 
mandatory assessment of 15 cents for each 100 pounds of milk 
produced and marketed in the 48 contiguous states producers may 
assign up to 10 cents of the assessment to regional or state 
qualified programs or qps that have similar promotional projects 
but at least 5 cents of the assessment must be sent to the 
national dairy promotion and research board or national dairy 
board which consists of 36 dairy farmers appointed by the 
secretary of agriculture 
the board finances national promotional programs including 
television commercials to help sell more milk and other dairy 
products all subject to review by ams officials 
according to the report which has been circulating recently 
within the dairy industry and the department auditors looked into 
the use of program funds during the period of may 1985 through may 
1987 and other periods as deemed necessary 
during that period approximately 291 billion pounds of milk 
were marketed with an assessment of around 4369 million of 
which almost 1682 million was remitted to the national board and 
2687 million credited to the qps 
the audit report said 
five of the 18 qps reviewed passed 147 million of 156 
million in assessment funds collected to other qps and incurred 
approximately 235000 in administrative costs 
two other qps improperly used 106500 for activities such as 
school activity funds athletic tournaments support of veterinary 
services the national future farmers of america foundation and 
other miscellaneous accounts 
five qps with assessments funds totaling about 205 million 
had internal control weaknesses such as separation of duties 
management of promotional materials and procurement systems 
four qps incurred 24 million in administrative costs in 
excess of the 5 percent limit set by the national dairy board 
in the absence of guidelines concerning the use of the 
assessment funds the qps and an affiliated organization the 
united dairy industry association of rosemont ill had only 
their discretion to follow the report said 
auditors said they questioned the associations classification 
of about 58 million of administrative costs as program costs 
1500 in monthly per diem to the udias chairman of the board of 
directors and 85 per diem per day in excess of travelrelated 
expenses to members of the udia board 
the report recommended a general tightening up of procedures 
including accounting by the qps on how the money is spent also 
the departments agricultural marketing service should devise and 
implement guidelines that organizations must follow before 
getting any funds 
in its comments the ams agreed to some of the audit reports 
recommendation but said its authority on others was limited and 
that action by congress may be required 
if the department concludes that such additional oversight is 
desirable ams would be willing to discuss with congress the 
purpose and legislative intent of the law authorizing the dairy 
promotion program the marketing service said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when it comes to curbing the cotton boll 
weevil its a matter of timing and tillage rather than how much 
pesticide is used the agriculture department says 
a sevenyear study in the lower rio grande valley of texas led 
to a new state law last year that requires farmers to destroy 
cotton stalks by sept 15 by shredding the stalks and then 
following up with deep plowing the destructive weevils are 
deprived of winter shelter and food when they are dormant 
entomologist kenneth r summy of the departments agricultural 
research service says in a report that the rio grande study showed 
that farmers applied pesticides 15 times to 18 times a year in 1980 
and 1981 
but in 1984 following a year of moderate stalk destruction 
chemicals only had to be applied three or four times he said from 
1985 to 1987 pesticide use rose again sometimes equaling 1981 
levels because farmers didnt destroy the cotton stalks 
last year the texas legislature passed the law requiring cotton 
growers to destroy stalks annually by sept 15 in the rio grande 
zone later in other parts of the state 
to help state officials enforce stalk destruction usda 
scientists worked out a surveillance system for cotton fields by 
using infrared aerial photos to detect which fields are not plowed 
by the deadline summy said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture departments 65th annual 
outlook conference has been scheduled for nov 29 through dec 1 
analysts from government and the private sector participate in 
the annual meetings to talk about the national and global 
economies agriculture and trade in the coming year 
sessions will include forecasts for major farm commodities 
including wheat corn soybeans cotton and meat other meetings 
will focus on food prices water quality conservation aquaculture 
and transportation 
