<TEXT>
the united states and its industrial allies 
are trying to slow the development of missiles in argentina brazil 
and north korea and hope to have the cooperation of the soviet 
union in the global campaign against proliferation 
the state department confirmed on monday that the seven allies 
meeting in rome sept 89 exchanged expressions of concern about 
missile proliferation and technology transfers that might enhance 
argentinas capability 
afterward a us official told the associated press the same 
group registered concern in its deliberations about programs in 
brazil and north korea 
the official who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
secretary of state george p shultz may pursue the problem with 
soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze during their talks 
in washington on thursday and friday 
in any event the official said assistant secretary of state h 
allen holmes will take up the issue at talks in washington next 
week with viktor p karpov senior soviet arms control negotiator 
north koreas attempt to extend the range of its scud b missile 
should demonstrate to the soviets the proliferation problem extends 
to their region the official said 
brazils attempt to develop the sonda iv missile is the other 
program the united states discussed with representatives of 
britain france west germany italy canada and japan the 
official said 
it was an attempt to keep everybody up to date in the area 
the official said they did not adopt any special program thats 
not the way it works 
meanwhile spokesman charles e redman referring to the 
mediumrange condor ii that argentina reportedly is developing with 
the help of egypt and iraq said the basic concern is that we do 
what we can to limit this kind of technology because it is the kind 
of technology that produces missiles that would be 
nuclearcapable 
he said they also would exceed the range of parameters we 
established meaning a range beyond 180 miles and a payload in 
excess of 1100 pounds 
the seven countries agreed last year that they would not export 
missiles or technology for them that went beyond these limits 
meanwhile an arab league representative voiced concern about 
israels launch monday of a test satellite into orbit and said it 
meant the arabs would have to strengthen their defenses 
clovis maksoud who represents the arab league in the united 
states said the satellite gave israel a serious strategic 
leverage since the country already had the capability to fire 
longrange missiles 
maksoud in an interview stressed steps taken jointly by israel 
and the united states to strengthen their strategic ties 
he cited us inclusion of israel in the program to develop a 
spacebased defense against ballistic missiles and israels 
record which is replete with disclaiming nuclear capability 
as a result maksoud said the launching of a test satellite 
warrants enhancing arab defensive capabilities so that any 
mideast negotiations produce a peaceful outcome rather than 
ratifying israeli hegemony 
the satellite is designed for communications purposes but the 
arab league official said it could be used to monitor israels foes 
we are deeply concerned that such a communications satellite 
can be modified into a spy system and therefore further enhance 
the strategic imbalance which the americanisraeli strategic 
agreement has introduced maksoud said 
state department spokesman redman said the united states was not 
involved in any way with the israeli program 
we dont have any details of the launch beyond what was 
reported by the israelis he said 
a spokesman for the us space command in colorado cmdr dugald 
gillies said american radars and sensors picked up the israeli 
satellite shortly after launch its orbit has been calculated to 
have a high point of 716 miles and a low point of 155 miles he 
said 
it was launched early monday eastern daylight time and is in a 
near polar orbit gillies said 
defense officials at the pentagon said they were unsure exactly 
what the satellites payload included 
but were leaning toward more of an experimental 
communications package as opposed to a true spy satellite said 
one source who spoke on condition of anonymity 
this launch is impressive because its a first but i dont 
think this particular satellite is going to offer much more ability 
to keep tabs on their neighbors the source said 
redman stressed that israeli leaders had given public assurances 
that their goal was peaceful purposes of space research and 
technological advancement 
israel is the eighth nation to place a satellite into space the 
country is generally believed to have nuclear capability 
</TEXT>
