president amin gemayel whose 6yearterm ends friday 
failure to elect a new president would plunge lebanon into a 
constitutional crisis that could trigger a new round of violence in 
the nations 13year civil war that has killed more than 130000 
people 
the police spokesman said skaffs three bodyguards also suffered 
minor wounds when the bomb filled with 110 pounds of tnt exploded 
the spokesman who cannot be named in line with police 
regulations said the other casualties were pedestrians motorists 
or shopkeepers 
the explosion the 13th car bombing in lebanon this year 
destroyed 43 cars parked in the street shattered glass and started 
several fires the spokesman said he said fire engines took an 
hour to put out the flames 
by police count 104 people have been killed and 378 wounded in 
the previous 12 car bombings 
a christian official speaking on condition of anonymity 
charged that the car bombing was designed to block the bkirki 
meeting 
however 27 of the 41 christian parliament deputies took part in 
the fourhour meeting at bkirki the seat of the maronite catholic 
patriarch nasrallah sfeir 12 miles north of beirut 
they met to try to agree on a presidential candidate after 
rejecting a syrianamerican agreement to name deputy mikhail daher 
a statement issued after the session said they will meet again 
wednesday after consulting with other nonchristian deputies 
the statement said christian deputies stress that parliament 
should convene thursday as called for by shiite moslem house 
speaker hussein husseini to elect a new president 
but they called on husseini to shift the meeting from the old 
parliament building in moslem west beirut to the villa mansour in 
the nomans land of the citys dividing green line to facilitate 
participation of christian deputies 
the date falls one day before gemayels term in office expires 
under the constitution he cannot seek a second consequtive term 
a spokesman for sfeir has said he expects the christian deputies 
to nominate veteran maronite politician raymond edde 
edde living in paris since 1976 after surviving three 
assassination attempts in beirut announced last week he will run 
for president 
edde is acceptable to moslem parliament deputies his 
nomination will create an atmosphere of democratic competition 
within parliament this is what we want to preserve said sfeirs 
spokesman who demanded anonymity 
edde told the associated press in a telephone interview from 
paris on saturday that if elected he will first seek an israeli 
withdrawal from a selfdesignated security zone in south lebanon 
then ask the syrians to leave 
he warned that unless he succeeds in forcing the israelis out 
he would not return to lebanon and would ask parliament to elect 
another president 
syrianbacked moslem and leftist leaders have threatened to 
declare a separate republic in territory they control if gemayel 
seeks to resolve the crisis by appointing a maronite prime minister 
to head a caretaker cabinet 
according to an unwritten national covenant dating to lebanons 
independence from france in 1943 the president should be a 
maronite house speaker a shiite and prime minister a sunni moslem 
christian deputies boycotted a session at villa mansour aug 18 
preventing parliament from mustering a quorum of 51 voters to elect 
a president 
the only serious candidate at the time was syrianbacked former 
president suleiman franjieh christians rejected him as too closely 
aligned with syria 
moslem politicians charged that the main christian militia was 
working at israels bidding to trying to undermine the elections 
syria the main power broker in lebanon maintains 40000 troops 
in eastern and northern provinces as well as west and south beirut 
</TEXT>
