<TEXT>
a federal jury tuesday convicted a british aircraft 
broker of trying to sell 10 embargoed us helicopters to iran 
the federal jury deliberated 90 minutes before finding colin 
breeze 34 of manchester england guilty of conspiring to falsify 
export documents in an attempt to hide the reexport of the used 
sikorsky s76 helicopters from jordan to iran 
his attorney laurie beloff said she would appeal 
breeze faces a maximum of 10 years in federal prison us 
district judge stanley marcus set sentencing oct 31 
breeze also had been indicted for soliciting others to falsify 
documents but marcus dismissed that count earlier tuesday ruling 
no such charge exists in federal law 
during trial breeze denied he intentially broke the law saying 
he was set up by a government informant who told him the sale was 
legal 
after the verdict breeze was returned to the federal 
metropolitan correctional center south of miami where he has been 
held since his arrest june 28 
breeze and codefendant graham reavell who apparently cannot be 
extradited from spain on the charges were accused of trying to win 
approval of the 30 million sale to iran by falsifying socalled 
end use certificates 
the certificates did not state iran was the ultimate destination 
for the helicopters which are ideal for transporting troops in the 
desert 
us customs service investigators allege the defendants worked 
with irans ambassador to spain 
</TEXT>
