a heavyset white woman in her 40s is 
pictured in a drawing released by a federal agency tuesday of a 
suspect in the july discovery of 13 time bombs planted in the small 
town of salem 
the bombs which caused no serious damage were found near 
buildings and under the bridges that provide the only access to the 
southern indiana community of about 6000 people 
the devices contained timers attached to as many as 26 sticks of 
gelatine dynamite and were packaged in paper grocery sacks they 
were concealed at various sites in and near the downtown square 
the drawing was released by the us bureau of alcohol tobacco 
and firearms and the indiana state police 
a military explosives expert said at the time that the bomber 
either lacked the expertise to properly wire the bombs or did not 
have an essential component 
three of the dynamite bundles exploded but produced only smoke 
and small fires the 10 others were defused by bomb experts 
no one was injured but authorities said the bombs could have 
caused widespread destruction 
