<TEXT>
the house on tuesday passed and sent to the 
senate a bill aimed at permitting the bureau of land management to 
resume transfers of land to western municipalities and counties for 
landfills 
the bill approved on a voice vote with minimal debate exempts 
landfills from the requirement in current law that land leased or 
sold to municipalities revert to the government if used for 
purposes not spelled out in the deed 
this requirement could leave the federal government liable for 
cleanup of any hazardous waste placed in municipal landfills the 
bureau concluded last year in suspending transfers of parcels for 
landfills 
more than 300 communities have acquired landfills this way 
the interior committee added a requirement to the bill that 
virgin land be inspected to make sure it contains no hazardous 
waste and that towns cities and counties getting these parcels 
pledge to follow hazardous waste laws and regulations 
but these requirements do not affect existing landfills 
rep mike synar dokla chairman of the environment and 
natural resources subcommittee of the government operations 
committee had sought tougher requirements from the interior 
committee his subcommittee reported two years ago that the bureau 
was ignoring guidelines promulgated by the environmental protection 
agency for landfills under the jurisdiction of federal agencies 
let me urge the blm to be responsible in moving land to 
municipal ownership including leased land synar said in a 
statement on the floor tuesday 
</TEXT>
