<TEXT>
the house on tuesday passed a bill that will 
allow federal agencies to locate in suburbs outside washington 
dc a move city officials said would mean a substantial loss in 
local taxes 
the bill which amends a 1959 law requiring that federal 
agencies be housed in the district of columbia was prompted by 
concern that federallyleased land within the city had become too 
expensive the bill passed by a voice vote now goes to the senate 
this legislation is important in that it would provide needed 
flexibility in the location of certain executive agencies in the 
national capital region at a significant savings to the 
government said rep glenn m anderson dcalif chairman of 
the public works and transportation committee 
average lease rates in the nations capital range from 27 to 
37 a square foot compared to only 18 to 22 per square foot in 
prince georges county md and 22 to 31 per square foot in 
alexandria va anderson noted 
a recent study by the general services administration the 
agency which handles all federal land purchases and rental 
agreements found that 6 million could be saved on a 10year lease 
of 100000 square feet if a federal agency moved to a suburban 
location 
rep guy molinari rny the bills chief sponsor said more 
than 50 independent agencies would be allowed to relocate outside 
washington 
however the legislation would not allow the principal offices 
of the 13 cabinetlevel agencies to move outside the district 
the fact of the matter is that we have the opportunity in many 
cases to lease equivalent space nearby in the suburbs at half of 
what it would cost to stay in the district said molinari 
were not anticipating any large massscale exodus but this 
could save millions and millions of taxpayer dollars 
but while the bill could ultimately mean a savings for federal 
taxpayers city officials said they will be scrambling to make up 
for the lost revenue 
this takes a lot of federal lease space in the district and 
sends it out to the suburbs said julius hobson the citys 
intergovernmental liason officer what we will lose is sales tax 
revenue from federal employees eating and shopping in the city 
hobson did not know exactly how much tax revenue the city would 
lose 
