a fire in a tunnel tuesday night delayed subway 
services at kings cross station the london fire service reported 
it was the second fire in the same spot in three days but no 
injures were reported in either blaze 
on nov 18 last year 31 people died and 80 were injured when 
fire broke out under an escalator at kings cross the london 
subway systems busiest station 
the fire service said in a statement that in tuesdays incident 
trash that had accumulated in the tunnel beween kings cross and 
euston the next subway station down the line caught fire but was 
quickly extinguished 
it said that on saturday services were briefly disrupted after 
a small fire broke out at the same spot that fire burned itself 
out before emergency crews arrived to tackle it 
the statement did not say what was thought to have caused the 
fires on tuesday and saturday 
investigators believe the nov 18 fire was started when a 
lighted cigarette was dropped on a wooden escalator surrounded by 
greasesoaked trash the fire raced up the escalator and a ball of 
flame exploded in the ticket lobby 
smoking has been banned throughout the subway system following 
the nov 18 fire but an independent inquiry into that fire 
expressed concern last june at the end of a 91day hearing that 
senior managers of london regional transport the public 
corporation that runs the subway might not accept the lessons of 
that disaster 
the inquirys chief counsel roger henderson accused senior 
managers of seeking to shirk responsibility for the fire the 
managers defended existing safety procedures but during the inquiry 
announced a package of 101 new safety measures 
