<TEXT>
a federal appeals court ruling barring a 
christianoperated manufacturing plant from requiring employees to 
attend prayer services will spark new rounds of court action a 
lawyer said tuesday 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals in san francisco ruled 
monday that townley engineering and manufacturing co of eloy 
ariz must allow employees to skip the services if they want to 
townley is expected to appeal the decision said mary jo oneil 
an antidiscrimination lawyer with the us equal employment 
opportunity commission the eeoc will seek to have the ruling 
applied to townleys other plants nationwide she added 
in addition the eeoc is already seeking contempt sanctions 
against townley over continued services at the plant and is 
appealing a lower court decision upholding the termination of an 
employee who objected to the services 
mondays 21 ruling requires the floridabased company to offer 
nonparticipation to employees whose religious convictions conflict 
with the service the ruling does not however ban the services 
outright as the eeoc had sought 
the plant about 55 miles southeast of phoenix makes mining 
equipment 
owners jake and helen townley say the business like the rest of 
their lives reflects their bornagain christian faith they 
enclose biblical tracts in all mail put biblical verses on 
business documents and require employees to attend 
nondenominational services during work hours once a week 
louis pelvas a machinist hired in 1979 attended the services 
for two months but then objected because he was an atheist 
pelvas left the company four months later and lost a damage 
lawsuit in which he contended he effectively had been fired but 
the eeoc lodged a complaint against the company charging religious 
discrimination 
us district judge earl carroll ruled in favor of the agency in 
may 1987 barring mandatory services at the plant the appeals 
court allowed services to resume while it considered the case but 
ruled monday that objectors must be allowed the option of staying 
away 
where the practices of employer and employee conflict it 
is not inappropriate to require the employer who structures the 
workplace to a substantial degree to travel the extra mile in 
adjusting its free exercise of religion rights if any to 
accommodate the employees rights said the opinion by judge 
joseph sneed 
the lone dissenter judge john noonan said townley had done 
enough by allowing the employee to wear ear plugs and read a 
newspaper while attending the services 
jake townley was not available for comment tuesday and helen 
townley who answered the telephone at the couples home said 
im not interested in talking about that today 
jake townley has said in depositions that he intends to follow 
gods law and continue with the services even if his actions 
conflict with us law and oneil said she did not expect him to 
back down 
