<TEXT>
the government outlined sweeping 
legislation tuesday to prevent funds reaching terrorists including 
new police powers and a change in bank secrecy laws 
home secretary douglas hurd unveiled the proposals at a police 
conference in this northwest resort town the measures will come 
before parliament next year police welcomed them but civil 
libertarians expressed some concern 
the time has come for firm action to throttle the flow of cash 
to terrorist organizations hurd said 
he said the laws include outlawing handling funds for 
terrorists freezing or confiscating these funds and freeing banks 
from secrecy rules so they can inform police of suspect deposits 
we shall draw the definition of terrorist purposes wide 
enough to catch anyone connected with this trade of death hurd 
said 
police will be able to seek warrants to get at relevant 
material including bank records of transactions he said 
the laws would bar handling assets that are to be used for 
terrorist purposes even if that activity is going on in an 
otherwise legitimate business hurd said 
a court convicting a person could confiscate any property or 
money that he has handled and that is intended for use in terrorist 
acts or in connection with terrorism hurd said adding the court 
would assume the money was tainted unless someone with an 
interest in it could show otherwise 
anticipating criticism hurd said while democracies need to 
consider long and hard before adopting such measures our 
conclusion is that the police and the courts must no longer lack 
the necessary powers to find and cut off the fuel which sustains 
the engines of murder 
the proposals were seen mainly as a weapon against the outlawed 
irish republican army which is fighting to rid northern ireland of 
british rule and unite the protestantdominated province with the 
95percent catholic irish republic 
sarah spencer general secretary of the national council for 
civil liberties objected to making the defendant prove funds were 
not destined for terrorist activity saying in many cases this 
could prove an impossible task 
alan wright a senior northern ireland police official welcomed 
the proposals 
if we can stop the iras money at source we can help prevent 
them buying arms and explosives he said no organization can 
last without funds 
protestant rev ian paisley leader of the democratic unionist 
party said the measures were too little too late he said the 
restrictions could be dodged by funneling the money to the outlawed 
iras legal political wing sinn fein 
britain claims one source for the estimated 85 million 
reaching ira coffers annually is noraid a proira fundraising 
group in the united states 
hurd did not spell out whether the new laws would affect noraid 
contributions but said bilateral agreements would be sought with 
foreign governments to help seize suspect funds 
