<TEXT>
tropical storm helene formed in the eastern 
atlantic on tuesday and showed potential for strengthening into a 
hurricane in the next day or two the national hurricane center 
reported 
helene is the eighth named storm of the 1988 atlantic hurricane 
season and the first since hurricane gilbert formed in the 
caribbean and went on to ravage jamaica and mexico 
helenes winds based on satellite photos reached 60 mph 
tuesday and was moving west at about 15 mph according an advisory 
from the hurricane center 
meteorologist randy lascody said a storm path cannot be 
projected until it moves closer to the caribbean 
its going across the warmest water of the year now which is 
perfect to fuel its growth lascody said tuesday night but it 
really would be very premature to give a guess on what may happen 
it still has a long way to go 
storms that form this month near the cape verde islands off 
africas coast are often the seasons strongest because of ideal 
hurricanespawning conditions forecasters say 
factors such as lowpressure zones in the caribbean and 
highlevel winds will affect the path of the storm said lascody 
it looks like it will reach its makeorbreak point sometime 
later this week he said 
the depression that became helene had initially seemed 
disorganized but satellite photos showed circulation had improved 
the hurricane center has not yet received ship reports on the 
storms intensity 
at 1030 pm edt helenes center was located 1500 miles east 
of the lesser antilles at latitude 12 north longitude 378 west 
it will take about four days for helene to get close enough to 
the caribbean to allow an air force reconnaissance plane to overfly 
the storm until then hurricane forecasters will have to rely on 
satellite reports said forecaster miles lawrence 
he emphasized there was no way to tell if helene would become as 
powerful as the deadly gilbert which forecasters have called the 
storm of the century 
gilbert which had winds about 175 mph at its peak did not 
reach tropical storm strength until reaching the caribbean 
</TEXT>
