<TEXT>
the prospect of naturally sweeter bread and 
new export markets is sparking fresh interest in the cultivation of 
hard white winter wheat in the plains states 
while the hard red variety has been king of the plains for more 
than a century a number of growers in kansas texas oklahoma 
nebraska and colorado are now giving white a try 
the american white wheat producers association which sprang 
from a group organized in kansas the nations no 1 
wheatproducing state says millers may pay premium prices for 
white wheat because it yields more flour per bushel 
white also has bread baking qualities comparable to hard red 
long the worlds premium bread wheat 
because of its lighter kernel color amber rather than the red 
more of the white wheat kernel can be ground and the flour is 
lighter in color than that of red wheat said don keesling 
president of the producers group 
the white wheat flour also has a slightly sweeter taste because 
the kernels lack the tannins that give red wheat bran a bitter 
taste keesling said thus bakers can save money by cutting down 
on sweetners normally used to offset the slight bitterness of red 
wheat flour 
my wife bakes with whole wheat flour from white wheat 
sometimes and people think the things taste sweeter even though 
the sugar in the recipe actually is reduced said keesling a 
chase kan farmer 
hard red wheat has been the favorite among us growers because 
it had the advantage of catching on first after russian immigrants 
introduced it to the great plains as a result little hard white 
wheat is now grown in the united states some is raised in montana 
and california and researchers in idaho and washington are 
experimenting with hard white varieties 
most of the white wheat cultivated in the united states is of 
the soft variety grown primarily in the pacific northwest and used 
in cookie and biscuit products 
the movement to hard white is small but organized the new 
producers group is incorporated as a marketing cooperative which 
controls the sale of the members white wheat said howard tice 
executive director of the kansas association of wheat growers 
the white wheat will be treated as a specialty crop and 
separated from hard red for marketing and storage to avoid mixing 
it with other varieties on the open market the white wheat will be 
sold on a contract basis by the cooperative 
keesling expects kansas growers to plant more than 2000 acres 
of hard white wheat this fall mostly in the western part of the 
state where growing conditions are best moister conditions in the 
east have caused the hard white wheat to exhibit head sprouting 
in which the kernels in the heads of the plants begin to sprout 
destroying the value of the grain for milling purposes 
kansas state university wheat breeders are working on a new 
variety with resistance to sprouting but it is several years down 
the road 
one ksu variety being tested this year may be released in 1989 
said joe martin a ksu wheat breeder stationed at the fort hays 
experiment station 
kurt feltner ksu associate agriculture dean and director of 
agriculture experiment stations said increased grower interest has 
given a dramatic boost to white wheat research begun in the late 
1950s 
within the past 18 months or so the administration has given 
us the green light to go ahead and increase our efforts because of 
the extraction rate and possible marketing niches for white 
wheat feltner said 
ktech inc a state economic development agency gave the 
university a 160000 grant that was matched with 160000 from the 
kansas wheat commission to work on white wheat and other wheat 
projects feltner said grain scientists are studying white wheat 
quality and end uses and agricultural economists are studying its 
market potential 
one of the areas being evaluated is white wheats export 
promise many of the worlds importing countries prefer white 
wheat said ksu breeder martin 
hopefully this would open up some new avenues in some 
traditionally australian white wheat markets martin said 
australian white has been a favorite in the soviet union the 
middle east and southeast asia us exporters would likely target 
some of those strongholds 
i think were probably a couple of years away from knowing 
whether white wheat is going to have an exciting start in kansas or 
whether its going to be a gradual transition said feltner 
</TEXT>
