<TEXT>
texaco inc will continue operating in 
ecuador until the ecuadoran government takes complete control over 
the pipeline and oilfield operations the two now run jointly a 
company spokesman announced tuesday 
ecuadors new center left government headed by president 
rodrigo borja announced monday night it woudl assume control of 
the transecuadorian pipeline next year and take over oilfield 
operations in 1990 when its contract with the state compania 
ecuatoriano de petroleo cepe expires 
texaco manages 375 percent of ecuadors petroleum industry oil 
accounts for about twothirds of ecuadors export revenue 
the announcement surprised us though we knew it would 
eventually happen rodrigo perez a texaco spokesman said at a 
quito press conference 
perez told reporters the government failed to notify texaco 
about its plans and said the us oil giant would have preferred 
prior talks with the government but he added the government is 
exercising its rights according to existing contracts 
under its agreements with texaco cepe can take over the 
companys operations provided it notifies the firm of its plans a 
year in advance 
a minor controversy arose monday when a government spokesman 
termed the takeover a nationalization the government later 
announced it simply was fulfilling the terms of its contract with 
texaco and not nationalizing its assets 
